# 1. Introduction to JavaScript

## Definition

JavaScript is a high-level, interpreted programming language mainly used to create interactive and dynamic web pages. 
It is one of the core technologies of web development along with HTML and CSS.

* HTML is used for structure.
* CSS is used for styling.
* JavaScript is used for functionality and interactivity.

JavaScript allows developers to create features like:

* Image sliders
* Form validation
* Pop-up messages
* Interactive maps
* Animations
* Dynamic content updates

---

## Example of JavaScript

```javascript
console.log("Hello World");
```

### Output:

```javascript
Hello World
```

This program prints “Hello World” in the browser console.

---

## Why JavaScript is Important

JavaScript is important because it makes websites interactive and user-friendly.

### Without JavaScript:

* Websites are static.
* No dynamic updates.
* Limited user interaction.

### With JavaScript:

* Websites become dynamic.
* Users can interact with content.
* Real-time updates are possible.

---

## Characteristics of JavaScript

* Lightweight language
* Object-oriented
* Event-driven
* Platform independent
* Interpreted language
* Supports functional programming

---

# 2. History of JavaScript

## Origin of JavaScript

JavaScript was created by Brendan Eich in 1995 while working at Netscape.

The language was developed in only 10 days for the Netscape Navigator browser.

---

## Earlier Names

JavaScript was originally called:

1. Mocha
2. LiveScript
3. JavaScript

The name “JavaScript” was chosen for marketing purposes because Java was very popular at that time.

---

## Standardization

JavaScript was standardized by:

* ECMA International

The official standard is called:

* ECMAScript

---

## Major Versions

| Version      | Year   | Features                                |
| ------------ | ------ | --------------------------------------- |
| ES1          | 1997   | First standard                          |
| ES5          | 2009   | Strict mode, JSON support               |
| ES6 (ES2015) | 2015   | let, const, classes, arrow functions    |
| ES7+         | Modern | Async/await, modules, advanced features |

---

